messages.content: Thanks, James!!

**📡  Validators Update - Minor - v2.1.0**
@itsai・32 

In this update we've added several features to make validators life easier and a little changed default params for running validator.

**Autoupdate**
After v2.1.0, updates should be downloaded and installed automatically if they contain only code/requirements changes. To run your code with autoupdate you have to use this command: `pm2 start run.sh --name llm_detection_validators_autoupdate -- --wallet.name YOUR_COLDKEY --wallet.hotkey YOUR_HOTKEY --axon.port 70000 --neuron.device cuda:0`

**WandB**
We've added wandb, where validators will log their metrics per each miner and where you can see which version each validator is currently running.

**Ollama autorestart on RunPod**
A few validators faced a problem that some server provider, including very popular RunPod, don't have systemd, which ollama uses to automatically restart itself when it stops. We found out that pm2 can take care of restarting ollama even without systemd.

To run ollama with pm2 kill all current instance of it and then run `pm2 start --name ollama "ollama serve"`

**Adjust moving_average_alpha**
In our subnet it takes a few minutes for validator to generate challenges for miners and we've decided adjust alpha to 0.1 as it is in text-prompting subnet, so that now new miners will stabilize faster after registration.

Feel free to pull a new version from our github page and go through validating.md docs to run a new version: https://github.com/It-s-AI/llm-detection/tree/main

**📡Validator Update - Major - v2.3.0**
@itsai・32 

**Data Source**
In the previous validation we used C4 dataset for human-written texts and generates different prompts for ai-generated content using the same approach as in the text-prompting subnet. Since now we moved to Pile dataset, which contain not only web-crawled data, but also about 20 different topics, including financial, med, law, arxiv, github and others.

To make the structure of data similar in ai-generated and human-written texts and avoid overfitting on the source of data, we now use Pile not only for human-written texts, but for generating ai samples as well (we use samples from dataset as a text begining and ask model to complete it).

**Models**
In the recent time there are appeared several new SOTA models for text generation, so we extending our model pull up to 15 models, including llama3, starling-lm:7b-beta, mixtral, command r and others. Plus we started to use raw models for text completion alongside with instructed finetuned.

Also to cover wider range of models and their settings we currently randomly select generation parameters (such as temperature, top_p, top_k and frequency_penaly) during validation.

**Data augmentation**
In addition we worked on the augmentation process. While in the previous version there were only about 5 type of augs, we now extended it up to 15, including letter capitalizing, spell correction and many char-based augs.

**Number of samples**
While we extended models pull and added more random in the validation process we decided to increase number of samples in one query up to 300 to make it more stable. Baseline solution still makes prediction in less than 2s, so time limit is not increased.

**❗️Requirements for update❗️**
New version need at least 150gb of free space, because we need to download many different models and at least 32gb of ram. To prevent crushing validators, which don't match this requirements we'll publish an update in 24h, so that validators can make sure that they match all criterias.

**⛏Miners sample data**

To make an update smoother without disabling registration we also decided to provide miners a sample of data from a new validation. In the file below you can find 600 samples with labels, which we took from a new validation. You can use this data to score your current solution and make sure that it isn't overfitted on the validation. Keep in mind that we publish new version in 24h from now.

Thanks for your feedback @NeuroChain, I'll try to clarify our validation process to you. 
1) We are using 15 different models for ai-text generation and yes, you can find some repeated texts because not so strong models sometimes cycling (I guess your samples was generated by gemma model), but you can check our query_samples.csv file (it was attached in the announce of v2.3) and see that example like yours are only corner cases while most of ai-gereated data is human-looking. I believe that while some models are prone to cycling it's good to have such piece of data too and these samples should be classified as ai-models.

2) Here is a short brief of our augmentation: we take a sample from Pile dataset, then randomly select subsequence of sentences (from 3 to 10) and after that add 1-2 char-based changes into it (it can be changing the char, removing space, inserting char and etc). 1-2 char changes doesn't make 7-sentences (on average) human-written texts ai-generated, but it simulate some ways that real users can try to overcome llm-detector and so miner's soulution should be stabel for such an augs.

3) Pile dataset is an improved version of C4. While the C4 dataset has only web-crawled texts, Pile dataset also contain about 20 different topics, including financial, med, law, arxiv, github and others (you can read more about Pile dataset here - https://arxiv.org/pdf/2101.00027). We believe that miner's should be able to handle all topics and determine whether the text were written by human or by ai-model regardless from the theme. It was the reason why we moved to Pile. 

About the difficulty of mining - we want miners to create a robust models, that can solve llm-detection with good quality, so no one said that it should be easy.

4) It's been already two weeks since our update. On one RTX 4090 you can generate 300 samples per 30 min. So, if you'd tried to generate date and used only 3 RTX 4090 you could already have more than 500k of samples and train your models based on them. The miner above somehow managed to adapt, so it's surely possible - you just have to work hard and compete with other clever guys, which is not easy.
